 "response_text": "The mean deviation between agents' held environmental values and their milk choice behaviors exhibits a pronounced trajectory characterized by an initial phase of rapid divergence followed by prolonged stabilization. At the 1974 baseline (time step 0), the deviation registers at zero, indicating complete alignment between consumer environmental valuations and their milk selections.\n\nDuring the first approximately nine time steps (representing the period from 1974 to roughly 1983), the deviation increases rapidly and significantly. The metric rises steeply from zero at a rate of approximately 2.84 units per time step in the earliest phase, then continues at a moderated but significant rate of 0.11 units per time step through the subsequent intervals. By time step 13 (approximately 1987), the deviation reaches its maximum value of 13.48, marking the peak misalignment between environmental values and consumption behaviors.\n\nFollowing this apex, the system enters a prolonged plateau phase spanning from approximately time step 13 through the conclusion of the simulation at time step 32 (2005). Throughout this latter period, the deviation stabilizes around a mean of approximately 13.43, exhibiting minor oscillations between peaks reaching 13.48 and valleys of 13.42. These fluctuations occur without significant directional trend, indicating that the system has reached a steady-state equilibrium. The terminal value of 13.42 at the final time step confirms the persistence of this elevated deviation throughout the final two decades of the simulation period.\n\nThis pattern suggests that as the milk market transitioned from whole milk dominance toward skimmed and semi-skimmed varieties, consumers increasingly maintained consumption habits that conflicted with their personal environmental values. The initial decade represents a period of accumulating cognitive dissonance as social influence, habit formation, and network effects drove adoption behaviors away from environmentally-aligned preferences. After approximately 1987, the deviation saturates, indicating that the population settled into a persistent state where milk choices consistently diverged from environmental valuations, with the interaction of Watts-Strogatz network topology, social conformity mechanisms, and habit thresholds preventing reconvergence despite ongoing post-choice evaluation processes."  
}

